  abstract = {OBJECTIVE: The aim was to develop and test a novel screen of adult ADHD, with a specific focus on clinical use. We designed a series of three studies to accomplish this aim. METHOD: Study One (n‚Äâ=‚Äâ155) and Study Two (n‚Äâ=‚Äâ591) collected data via surveys to conduct exploratory and confirmatory factor analyses, respectively. Study Three analyzed the scale's psychometrics in a clinical sample (n‚Äâ=‚Äâ151). RESULTS: Study One and Study Two identified a 10-item scale with a two-factor structure. Study Three found good discriminant validity, sensitivity‚Äâ=‚Äâ80.0%, specificity‚Äâ=‚Äâ80.2%, and convergent validity with both the Brown Executive Function/Attention Scales, r (131)‚Äâ=‚Äâ.76, p‚Äâ<‚Äâ.001, and the Conner's Adult ADHD Rating Scales r (131)‚Äâ=‚Äâ.71, p‚Äâ<‚Äâ.001. CONCLUSION: The scale demonstrated effectiveness in screening for ADHD in a psychiatric outpatient population. Its results may be used to identify patients that may benefit from thorough ADHD diagnostic procedures.},
